<span class="displaytext"><b><u>"this incident reveals a true anti-farming slant to the (candidate last) campaign"</u></b> <p><b>gov. tim pawlenty on abc's <i>good morning america: </i>(candidate last) not offering "positive vision" for iowa farmers. </b>bill weir: "people want to follow hopeful, optimistic, civil, decent leaders. are those qualities what has him so far ahead in the polls, do you think? and how would you relate those qualities to the (candidate last) campaign?" gov. tim pawlenty: "well, i think whether its (candidate full) or anyone else, people want to see a hopeful, positive vision for the future of the country, but that's not what (candidate full)'s been offering. for example, here in iowa, he said recently to joel klein of <i>time</i> magazine, that agriculture is to blame for the nation's health problems partly, including diabetes and heart disease and others. you can imagine what iowa farmers are going to think of that." weir: "well, i think he was talking about corn syrup in soda and fast food. that's a little bit out of context. i won't ask --" gov. pawlenty: "but bill, farmers don't grow soda, they grow corn." (abc's "good morning america," 11/1/08) </p><p><b><i>commentary magazine's</i></b><b> jennifer rubin: (candidate last)'s rural "condescension" slips out. </b>"in loose moments, (candidate last)'s lack of understanding of and condescension toward rural and small-town america always slips out. and really, is his point that if farmers grew less food, americans would be thinner? the mind reels." (jennifer rubin, "(candidate last) to farmers: stop growing food," <i>commentary magazine </i>contentions blog," <a href="http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/rubin/40941">http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/rubin/40941</a>, 11/1/08)<b> </b></p><p><b><i>bemidji (mn) pioneer: </i></b><b>sen. grassley: "it is ludicrous to blame farmers for obesity." </b>"'it is ludicrous to blame farmers for obesity and pollution,' sen. charles grassley, r-iowa, told reporters during a friday conference call. 'i think he really doesn't understand agriculture.'" (don davis and scott wente, "campaign notebook: (candidate last) comments upset gop farmers," <i>bemidji pioneer</i>, 11/1/08) </p><p><b><i>st. paul pioneer press: </i></b><b>sen. grassley: (candidate last) "doesn't have a very good foundation." </b>"in a conference call arranged by the (candidate last) campaign, sen. charles grassley, r-iowa, called it 'ludicrous to blame farmers for obesity and pollution.' said grassley: 'it shows that sen. (candidate last) doesn't have a very good foundation in american agriculture.'" (tom webb, "(candidate last) faults (candidate last)'s comments on farming," <i>st. paul pioneer press, 11/1/08)</i><i> </i></p><p><b><i>st. paul pioneer press: </i></b><b>sen. grassley: (candidate last) gets ag ideas from "professor at cal-berkeley." </b>"(p)eople in agriculture need to know that if sen. (candidate last) is going to get his ideas on agriculture from a professor at cal-berkeley, they should think twice about what they are voting for." (tom webb, "(candidate last) faults (candidate last)'s comments on farming," <i>st. paul pioneer press, 11/1/08)</i><b><i></i></b></p><p>des moines register: <b>farmer ron litterer: "no question about" (candidate last)' s conflicting message to farmers. </b>"but ron litterer, a greene farmer who is chairman of the national corn growers association, said (candidate last)'s comments in the <i>time</i> interview were 'in conflict with what he's been saying about agriculture, no question about it.'" (philip brasher, "(candidate last) links health issues to farming, then backs off," <i>des moines register, </i>10/31/08) </p><p><b><i>hoosier ag today's </i></b><b>gary truitt: (candidate last)'s "true anti-farming slant." </b>"in my view this incident reveals a true anti-farming slant to the (candidate last) campaign and demonstrates a fundamental lack of support for farmers." (gary truitt, "(candidate last), open mouth-insert foot," hat chat, the official blog of <i>hoosier ag today, <a href="http://hatchat.net/">http://hatchat.net/</a>, </i>10/31/08) </p><p>• <b>truitt: "major blunder" </b>"(candidate last), however, has made a major blunder by quoting (michael) pollan, an outspoken critic of agriculture and an environmental radical." (gary truitt, "(candidate last), open mouth-insert foot," hat chat, the official blog of <i>hoosier ag today, <a href="http://hatchat.net/">http://hatchat.net/</a>, </i>10/31/08) </p><p>• <b>truitt: "unlike (candidate last), (candidate last) stuck to his position" </b>"early in the campaign (candidate full) was criticized by the ag community, and this blog, for his comments on the ethanol subsidy. unlike (candidate last), (candidate last) stuck to his position and explained he was against all subsidies and had nothing against ethanol." (gary truitt, "(candidate last), open mouth-insert foot," hat chat, the official blog of <i>hoosier ag today, <a href="http://hatchat.net/">http://hatchat.net/</a>, </i>10/31/08)<b></b></p></span>



